Step-by-step explanation:
1. The question asks about the Monopoly board and which property forms a set with Coventry Street and Leicester Square.
2. In the reference material, the document titled "List of London Monopoly locations" explains that the Monopoly locations are set in London and were selected in 1935 by Victor Watson.
3. It is known (from general Monopoly knowledge) that in the standard British version of the game, the properties are grouped into color-coded sets.
4. Coventry Street and Leicester Square are both part of the same color set in Monopoly.
5. The property that completes the set with Coventry Street and Leicester Square is Piccadilly. This is because, in the British version of Monopoly, these three properties (Coventry Street, Leicester Square, and Piccadilly) form the orange-colored set.
